# CSV Parser - Code Examples

Comprehensive examples demonstrating all features of the CSV parser library.

## Table of Contents
1. [Basic Parsing](#basic-parsing)
2. [Type Coercion](#type-coercion)
3. [Quoted Fields](#quoted-fields)
4. [Custom Configuration](#custom-configuration)
5. [Filtering](#filtering)
6. [Aggregation](#aggregation)
7. [Error Handling](#error-handling)
8. [Real-World Use Cases](#real-world-use-cases)

---

## Basic Parsing

### Simple CSV

```javascript
const { parseCSV } = require('./csv-parser.js');

const csv = `name,age,email
John,30,john@example.com
Jane,25,jane@example.com
Bob,35,bob@example.com`;

const result = parseCSV(csv);

console.log(result.headers);
// Output: ['name', 'age', 'email']

console.log(result.rows);
// Output:
// [
//   { name: 'John', age: 30, email: 'john@example.com' },
//   { name: 'Jane', age: 25, email: 'jane@example.com' },
//   { name: 'Bob', age: 35, email: 'bob@example.com' }
// ]

console.log(result.errors);
// Output: []
```

### Accessing Data

```javascript
// Get specific field from first row
const firstName = result.rows[0].name;  // 'John'

// Iterate through all rows
result.rows.forEach(row => {
  console.log(`${row.name} is ${row.age} years old`);
});
// John is 30 years old
// Jane is 25 years old
// Bob is 35 years old

// Map to new format
const names = result.rows.map(row => row.name);
// ['John', 'Jane', 'Bob']
```

---

## Type Coercion

### Multiple Data Types

```javascript
const csv = `id,product,price,quantity,active,rating,notes
1,Widget,19.99,100,true,4.5,Popular item
2,Gadget,29.50,50,false,,New release
3,Tool,9.99,0,true,null,In stock
4,Device,99.00,25,false,3.2,`;

const result = parseCSV(csv);

// Examine first row
const row1 = result.rows[0];
console.log(typeof row1.id);        // 'number' -> 1
console.log(typeof row1.price);     // 'number' -> 19.99
console.log(typeof row1.quantity);  // 'number' -> 100
console.log(typeof row1.active);    // 'boolean' -> true
console.log(typeof row1.rating);    // 'number' -> 4.5
console.log(row1.notes);            // 'string' -> 'Popular item'

// Examine row with nulls
const row2 = result.rows[1];
console.log(row2.rating);           // null (empty field)
console.log(typeof row2.rating);    // 'object' (null is an object in JS)

// Examine row with null text
const row3 = result.rows[2];
console.log(row3.rating);           // null (explicit "null" string)

// Type coercion works even with whitespace
console.log(result.rows[0].id);     // 1 (number)
```

### Boolean Case Insensitivity

```javascript
const csv = `name,value
Item1,true
Item2,True
Item3,TRUE
Item4,false
Item5,False
Item6,FALSE`;

const result = parseCSV(csv);

result.rows.forEach((row, i) => {
  console.log(`Row ${i + 1}: ${row.name} = ${row.value} (type: ${typeof row.value})`);
});
// Row 1: Item1 = true (type: boolean)
// Row 2: Item2 = true (type: boolean)
// Row 3: Item3 = true (type: boolean)
// Row 4: Item4 = false (type: boolean)
// Row 5: Item5 = false (type: boolean)
// Row 6: Item6 = false (type: boolean)

// Use in logic
const trueCount = result.rows.filter(r => r.value === true).length;
console.log(`${trueCount} true values`);  // 3 true values
```

### Float vs Integer

```javascript
const csv = `name,integer,float,string
A,100,100.5,100.5abc
B,0,0.0,007
C,42,42.0,42`;

const result = parseCSV(csv);

result.rows.forEach(row => {
  console.log({
    integer: row.integer,
    intType: typeof row.integer,
    float: row.float,
    floatType: typeof row.float,
    string: row.string,
    stringType: typeof row.string
  });
});
// Row A:
// { integer: 100, intType: 'number', 
//   float: 100.5, floatType: 'number', 
//   string: '100.5abc', stringType: 'string' }
```

